ठगड़ा बांध (Thagda Dam/Thagda Bandh) में सनसेट प्वाइंट एक ख़ास आकर्षण है, जहाँ शाम के समय आप सुंदर-orange रंग के आसमान और शांत जल में उस प्रतिबिंब का आनंद ले सकते हैं। स्थानीय लोग और परिवार अक्सर शाम 6 से 7 बजे के बीच यहां पहुँचते हैं, क्योंकि उस समय सूरज ढलते ही पूरे दृश्य में सौंदर्य और रोमांटिक माहौल बन जाता है  ।

क्यों खास है यहाँ का सनसेट:

ब्रिज और आइलैंड से दृश्य: बांध के बीच बना छोटा पुल (आइलैंड कनेक्टिंग ब्रिज) झिलमिलाती लाइटिंग के साथ सनसेट के समय फोटोग्राफी के लिए बेहतरीन बैकड्रॉप तैयार करता है  ।

शांत और रोमांटिक माहौल: पानी और आसमान के रंगों का मिलन शांत और मनोहारी माहौल प्रदान करता है—पर्यटक और स्थानीय लोगों के लिए यह एक पसंदीदा पल होता है  ।

सुविधायें साथ: पास में छोटे-फूड कोर्ट, चाय-नाश्ता स्टॉल और बैठने की व्यवस्था है, जिससे आप आराम से सूरज ढलने का लुत्फ उठा सकते हैं  ।

टिप्स:

समय: सूरज ढलने से लगभग 30-45 मिनट पहले (शाम 5:30–6 बजे) पहुंचना अच्छा है।

कैमरा साथ रखें: यह समय फोटो शूट के लिए शानदार होता है।

भीड़: वीकेंड और छुट्टी के दिन शाम को अपेक्षाकृत भीड़ रहती है—यदि आप थकावट से परेशान नहीं हैं तो वहीं ठहर सकते हैं, अन्यथा ताज़गी भरा अनुभव मिलेगा।

🌅 अंतिम विचार:
ठगड़ा बांध का सनसेट प्वाइंट न सिर्फ प्राकृतिक सौंदर्य बल्कि पल-भर के आराम और यादगार फोटोग्राफी के लिए शानदार जगह है। सप्ताहांत की शाम ऐसी खूबसूरत जगह पर अपने बहुमूल्य पल बिताएं!

most_relevant.description: Maitri Bagh Zoo, Bhilai, a joint effort by India and Soviet Union and oldest zoo, is a delightful family outing. We enjoyed the pelicans, a large variety of birds, playful monkeys, storks and several deer species — the Bengal and white tigers were particularly majestic. The gardens are very well maintained with abundant trees, photographic sculptures and ample parking. The boating on the lake is relaxing and adds to the experience. Overall the park is clean, shady and child-friendly; great for weekend family visits.

Maitri Bagh, located in Bhilai, Chhattisgarh, is a well-known zoo and park that symbolizes the friendship between India and the Soviet Union. Its name translates to "Friendship Garden". Maintained by the Steel Authority of India Limited, it is one of the largest and oldest zoos in the region.

Maitri Bagh Zoo
Various types of birds, animals and aquatic animals are found here including white Tiger, Lion, Barahsingha are major attractions here. The park is full of greenary and peace. You can also the enjoy the boat ride.
Best time to visit is August to Feb - March

While my experience was great, I have a few suggestions that could enhance future visits:
Zoo Enclosure Maintenance: I noticed that some of the animal enclosures, particularly in the older sections of the zoo, could benefit from more consistent and detailed maintenance to improve hygiene and the overall presentation of the habitats.
Clarity of Service Timings: While the park and zoo timings are known, the operational times for attractions like the Boating and Toy Train were not immediately clear upon entry. Clearer signboards indicating the current operating hours for all activities would be very helpful.
Restroom Facilities: The cleanliness and upkeep of the public restroom facilities could be improved, particularly during peak hours, to match the standard of cleanliness maintained in the main garden areas.
Thank you once again for maintaining such a beautiful and valuable recreational space for the residents and visitors of Bhilai. I look forward to visiting again soon.

Biodiversity parks are unique landscapes composed of diverse communities that provide environmental , cultural and educational benefits to urban society. They provide multiple environmental services including  carbon sequestration, replenishment of aquifers, and educational and recreational benefits to the urban society. The biodiversity park with its rich flora and fauna is an ideal tool for promoting conservation education that ultimately has a positive impact on environmental quality and conservation ethics.

Cities are totally dependent on natural resources and biodiversity to meet their needs for essential goods and services . The lack of biodiversity affects a city’s growth and well being. A healthy ecosystem and organic range are essential for the smooth functioning of our cities and thus of the Country. The population of a city is much denser than that of a rural area, so it is more important to conserve the urban biodiversity.

Jama Masjid, Bhilai is one of the largest mosques in Chhattisgarh, India, with a capacity to accommodate more than 3000 worshippers at a time. It is the first mosque in the world to be built in the shape of the word "Ya Allah" in Arabic script. It took three years for the construction of the mosque which was completed in 1967.

HistoryEdit

Before the construction of the mosque the Muslims of Bhilai used to pray in their respective localities and gathered only on Eid al-Fitr and Eid al-Adha to offer common prayer near Nehru house of Culture in sector-1, Bhilai. The Muslim executives of Bhilai steel plant formed a committee and applied for its registration. It was registered as Bhilai Nagar Masjid Trust under Madhya Pradesh public Trust act 1951. The Bhilai steel plant allotted a plot measuring 12000 square feet in sector-6 to this committee for the Mosque. The construction began in 1964 and was completed in 1967. The first Friday prayer was held in the new mosque on 31 March 1967.

Architecture and designEdit

The special design of the mosque has created a history in the world of Islamic architecture through its monumental elevation which forms an Arabic word Yā Allāh (یا الله). The 80 feet high minar shapes ‘Ya’ while the concrete walls of the first floor with a slab above in the shape of tashdeed projects ‘Allah’. The marble dome at the top further enhances the beauty of this unique mosque in the world.

It was designed by the renowned architect Khairuddin Ahmad Siddiqui, Siddiqui and associates, Hyderabad, Telangana.

The mosque is 59 feet high, including the 16 feet high dome, 120 feet long and 100 feet wide. The Eid-gah adjacent to the mosque is 250 feet long and 230 feet wide. Marble tiles have been fixed inside and outside of the mosque’s minar. The mosque is maintained by the founding committee Bhilai Nagar Masjid Trust.

ImamsEdit

Alhaj Hafiz Sayed Ajmaluddin Haider served as the first Imam of this Mosque from 1968 to 2013. Born in Patna in 1942, his family moved permanently to Durg in 1952. His father, Maulana Afzaluddin Haidar became Imam of Jama Masjid Durg since 1952 whose mazaaris in Supela Kabristan, Bhilai. Alhaj Hafiz Sayed Ajmaluddin Haider is affiliated to Qadiriyyah Chishtiya Ashrafiya order of Sufism and is educated from Darul Uloom Islamia Nagpur.

Hafiz Iqbal Haider Anjum is the current Imam of the mosque who started serving from 1 January 2014. He is educated from Jame Ashraf, Kichaucha Shareef, Faizabad in Uttar Pradesh.

Welfare and developmentEdit

A Muslim community hall is built near mosque by the Bhilai Nagar masjid trust with the help of Muslims in Bhilai. The hall is 90 feet long, 42 feet wide and 22 feet high. A ladies’ hall has been partitioned out of it with approximately half of the total dimensions of the hall. The second floor is under construction and is estimated to be completed by the end of July 2015.

Jama Masjid, Bhilai is one of the largest mosques in Chhattisgarh, India, and also in Asia with a capacity to accommodate more than 3000 worshippers at a time. It is the first mosque in the world to be built in the shape of the word "Ya Allah" in Arabic script. It took three years for the construction of the mosque which was completed in 1967.

The special design of the mosque has created a history in the world of Islamic architecture through its monumental elevation which forms an Arabic word Yā Allāh (یا الله). The 80 feet high minar shapes ‘Ya’ while the concrete walls of the first floor with a slab above in the shape of tashdeed projects ‘Allah’. The marble dome at the top further enhances the beauty of this unique mosque in the world.

It was designed by the architect Khairuddin Ahmad Siddiqui, Siddiqui and associates, Hyderabad, Telangana.

The mosque is 59 feet high, including the 16 feet high dome, 120 feet long and 100 feet wide. The Eid-gah adjacent to the mosque is 250 feet long and 230 feet wide. Marble tiles have been fixed inside and outside of the mosque’s minar. The mosque is maintained by the founding committee Bhilai Nagar Masjid Trust.
